1 Introduction

The method of PethÅ‘ [8] (see also [5]) gives a fast algorithm to calculate â€smallâ€ solutions of Thue equations. The method is based on the continued fraction algorithm. By â€smallâ€ solutions we mean those with absolute values less than, say 10500superscript10500NUMBER:10 POSTSUPERSCRIPT:start NUMBER:500 POSTSUPERSCRIPT:end10^{500}. Nobody belives that such equations have larger solutions. All our experiences show that such equations usually only have a few very small solutions.

In this paper we make this algorithm more efficient in order to calculate â€smallâ€ solutions of a special type of Thue equations, the binomial Thue equations of type

3 Computational aspects

We were executing the algorithm of [8] with C=10500ğ¶superscript10500italic-C RELOP:equals NUMBER:10 POSTSUPERSCRIPT:start NUMBER:500 POSTSUPERSCRIPT:endC=10^{500} for n=ğ‘›absentitalic-n RELOP:equalsn= 3, 4, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 29 (the case n=4ğ‘›4italic-n RELOP:equals NUMBER:4n=4 was dealt with in [6]) using the above sharp estimates that made the procedure for binomial Thue equations much more efficient. This efficient algorithm allowed us to perform the calculations for all those 2â‰¤mâ‰¤1072ğ‘šsuperscript107NUMBER:2 RELOP:less-than-or-equals italic-m RELOP:less-than-or-equals NUMBER:10 POSTSUPERSCRIPT:start NUMBER:7 POSTSUPERSCRIPT:end2\leq m\leq 10^{7} for which the left side of (1) is irreducible.

The procedure was implemented in Maple [4], we used 1200 digits accuracy. For each exponent this calculation involved almost 107superscript107NUMBER:10 POSTSUPERSCRIPT:start NUMBER:7 POSTSUPERSCRIPT:end10^{7} binomial Thue equations. The routines were running on the supercomputer (high performance computer) network situated in Debrecen-Budapest-PÃ©cs-Szeged in Hungary under Linux. For each exponent the total running time was about 120-200 hours calculated for a single node which yields a few hours using parallel computing with a couple of nodes.
